  res.json({ status: 'ok' });
  // Move detailed health checks to /internal/health behind auth
});
```

---

## 🟡 LOW Severity

### 7. No Error Handling Middleware (OWASP A09: Security Logging & Monitoring Failures)

Unhandled errors will return Express's default error page, which can leak stack traces in development mode.

**Recommendation:**

```js
// Place AFTER all routes
app.use((err, req, res, next) => {
  console.error(`[${new Date().toISOString()}] ${err.message}`, {
    path: req.path,
    method: req.method,
    ip: req.ip,
  });
  res.status(500).json({ error: 'Internal server error' });
  // NEVER send err.stack or err.message to the client
});
```

### 8. Express Server Fingerprinting

Express sends `X-Powered-By: Express` by default, revealing the tech stack to attackers.

**Recommendation:**

```js
app.disable('x-powered-by');
// Or use helmet(), which does this automatically
```

### 9. No Request Size Limits

When body parsing is added, there should be explicit size limits to prevent large-payload DoS:

```js
app.use(express.json({ limit: '10kb' }));
app.use(express.urlencoded({ extended: false, limit: '10kb' }));
```

